Module - 1

1) Explain the OSI reference model?
A) The OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) model is a 7-layer conceptual framework developed by ISO to standardize network communication. It describes how data moves from one device to another.
    Layers (bottom to top):
    Layer 1: Physical – Bits, cables, signals.
    Layer 2: Data Link – Frames, MAC addressing, error detection.
    Layer 3: Network – Packets, IP addressing, routing.
    Layer 4: Transport – Segments, TCP/UDP, end-to-end delivery.
    Layer 5: Session – Manages sessions/connections.
    Layer 6: Presentation – Data formatting, encryption, compression.
    Layer 7: Application – User interface, protocols like HTTP, FTP.

2) What is a Network?
A) A network is a collection of interconnected devices (computers, servers, printers, etc.) that can share resources and communicate with each other.
3) What are Routers?
A) Routers are Layer 3 devices that connect multiple networks and forward packets between them based on IP addresses. They determine the best path using routing tables and protocols.
4) Explain Encapsulation.
A) Encapsulation is the process of adding header (and sometimes trailer) information to data as it moves down the OSI/TCP/IP stack. Each layer adds its own control information. De-encapsulation removes this information at the receiving end.
5) Peer-to-Peer Communication.
A) It is the process where each layer of the OSI model on the source device communicates directly with the same layer on the destination device using protocol data units (PDUs).
6) What is TCP and UDP?
A) TCP (Transmission Control Protocol): Connection-oriented, reliable, uses sequencing, acknowledgments, and flow control. Used for web, email.
  UDP (User Datagram Protocol): Connectionless, unreliable, faster, low overhead. Used for video streaming, DNS, VoIP.

7) What is Internetwork Operating System software?
A) IOS (Internetwork Operating System) is Cisco's proprietary operating system used on routers and switches. It provides the CLI for configuration and management.
8) Explain LAN and draw any example.
A) LAN (Local Area Network) is a network covering a small geographic area like a building or campus.
   Example: A company office with PCs, printers, and servers connected via switches and a router.
9) Explain Network Device – Router, Switch and Hub.
A)   Hub: Layer 1 device, broadcasts all traffic (creates one collision domain).
    Switch: Layer 2 device, forwards based on MAC addresses, creates separate collision domains per port.
    Router: Layer 3 device, forwards based on IP addresses, connects different networks.

10) Describe Router and switch connection in LAN.
 A) Switches connect end devices (PCs) within the LAN. The router connects the LAN to other networks (WAN/Internet) and performs inter-VLAN routing if needed.
11)  Types of Cable – explain types of Ethernets and speed.
A) Coaxial: Older, used in bus topologies.
  Twisted Pair (UTP/STP): Most common – Cat5e (1 Gbps), Cat6 (10 Gbps), Cat6a (10 Gbps+).
  Fiber Optic: Single-mode (long distance), Multi-mode (short distance). High speed, immune to EMI.
  Ethernet speeds: 10 Mbps, 100 Mbps (Fast), 1 Gbps (Gigabit), 10 Gbps, 40/100 Gbps.

12) Explain TCP/IP – List of Protocol and port Number.
 A)   TCP/IP is the suite of protocols used on the internet.
    Common protocols & ports:
    HTTP: TCP 80
    HTTPS: TCP 443
    FTP: TCP 20/21
    SSH: TCP 22
    Telnet: TCP 23
    SMTP: TCP 25
    DNS: UDP/TCP 53
    DHCP: UDP 67/68

13) Explain Node (backbone) and Physical layer.
A)  Node: Any device with a network address (PC, router, switch).
  Backbone: High-speed central network connecting multiple LANs.
  Physical Layer: Deals with transmission of raw bits over physical media (cables, signals, connectors).
